    "summary": "\"The metaphysical\" is better; \"object\" misleads",
    "content": "**\"The metaphysical\"** is better. Concise reasoning:\n\n\"Metaphysical object\" implies a thing -- an entity with independent existence. This directly contradicts the author's point. The entire argument of 后形而上学 is that 形而上 are *constructions upon phenomena*, not entities. They are patterns of constancy extracted from experience and then mistakenly reified as generators of experience (the 道德仁义礼 reversal). Calling them \"objects\" completes exactly the reification the author is warning against.\n\n\"The metaphysical\" as a substantive adjective preserves the right ambiguity: it names something without committing to what kind of thing it is. It can refer to a concept, a pattern, a construction, a universal property -- all of which 形而上 can be in different contexts.\n\nIn the formal definition from Essay 6 -- \"a metaphysical $m$ is an association in $\\mathcal{E}$, and $m$ is a universal property in some subcategory\" -- $m$ is a *morphism* (an association/联想), not an object in the standard sense. In category theory, morphisms and objects have equal ontological standing in an arrows-only metacategory, which the author explicitly notes. \"Metaphysical object\" would mislead mathematically literate readers into thinking $m$ is an object in $\\text{Obj}_\\mathcal{E}$ rather than a morphism that also functions as an object in the tower structure.\n\n**One exception**: When the author discusses 第三种形而上 (the third kind of metaphysical -- frameworks, value systems), \"the metaphysical\" still works but may benefit from occasional expansion to \"metaphysical construction\" or \"metaphysical framework\" for clarity. These are contextual choices, not a change in the base rendering."
  }
